snippet.textDisplay:
And English ruined Creative Writing, I loved to write and I was excited to do creative writing but the deadlines and the pressure made me force out a story I didn't like, it didn't matter if someone complimented me for it, I didn't like it, I wasn't used to short stories. And they had us do just one, what the heck just one idea and be done with it?
And the rest of the stuff was looking at a picture and they were like "What makes this so meaningful?" uhh can you stop imposing opinions like fact? and I thought we were trying to be creative, not necessarily artistic.


Same thing Graphics and Drawing and Media Studies with Film
"Oh which architect are you getting inspired by?" I don't want such limits.
"Oh which film is similar to your film?" Uh I came up with it myself I didn't base it off anything, You're gonna see it anyway why do you need a basis!

snippet.textDisplay: While I'll admit it has sometimes given me the opportunity to read a book I wouldn't have otherwise and find out that I REALLY liked it while and after reading it, F*CK school for forcing so many different books and novels and F*CKING poems down my throat! I never liked poetry, but do you know by how much was my hatred for them was amplified because of school? They'd teach us about a type of poem, make us read the one from the class manual, write a 3 pages/300 words long "review"/analysis of it (it's supposed to be a review, you know, your own opinion, but they all had to follow a strict set of guidelines and writing formulas, and God forbid you strayed from them or, even worse, SAY something negative about the work or that you didn't like it, cause if you did, the teachers would literally lower your grade) (I mean, mine didn't for liking or disliking, thankfully, but others did). We would spend literal weeks on assignments I couldn't give less of a shit about. And after 4 years of this shit during high school, I decided that, out of spite, I would neither read nor analize any of the mandatory poems for the graduation exam (which I've already had to do throughout high school), and I did it! In Romania, grad exams are divided between main subject, and for romanian the exam was split into 3 part: part 1, grammatical deconstruction of a given excerpt (meaning we'd get exercises like "what does this "," signify in this paragraph"); part 2, write a 1 page/100 words story about a given subject; part 3, analysis of either a poem/novel studied in class. Whichever type of excerpt you were given during part 1, in part 3 you were given the opposite; if you had an excerpt from a poem, you'd have to analyze a novel they gave you and vice versa, and I banked on it. I literally risked my grade out of sheer hatred for poetry, read nothing, learn nothing, do nothing. I basically said "f*ck you" to poetry, and banked it all on the split chance that we'd either have to write an analysis on a novel or a poem. And it paid out! Poetry during part 1, analysis of a mini novel called "Wheel of fortune" during part 3! I literally learned nothing about poetry, and I didn't get punished for it

snippet.textDisplay: As much as I dislike reading the only thing I could get past is that you can choose the book you want for a book report but back when I was in grade school my situation was choir class. I don't like to sing. At all. I never understood why schools have singing classes. Why are they even mandatory in the first place other than getting a (pointless) grade for it. My biggest question is why couldn't choir class be optional? Therefore if someone has a desire to be a singer then choir would be right their alley. It's not like singing is going to save my life or anything.
